In [[mathematics]], a '''semigroup with two elements''' is a [[semigroup]] for which the [[cardinality]] of the [[underlying set]] is [[two]]. There are exactly five [[distinct (mathematics)|distinct]] [[isomorphic|nonisomorphic]] semigroups having two elements:
* O<sub>2</sub>, the [[null semigroup]] of order two,
* LO<sub>2</sub> and RO<sub>2</sub>, the [[left zero semigroup]] of order two and [[right zero semigroup]] of order two, respectively,
* ({0,1}, ∧) (where "∧" is the [[logical connective]] "[[Logical conjunction|and]]"), or equivalently the set {0,1} under multiplication: the only [[semilattice]] with two elements and the only non-null semigroup with [[Null semigroup#Zero element in a semigroup|zero]] of order two, also a [[monoid]], and ultimately the [[two-element Boolean algebra]], 
* (Z<sub>2</sub>, +<sub>2</sub>) (where Z<sub>2</sub> = {0,1} and "+<sub>2</sub>" is "addition modulo 2"), or equivalently the set {−1,1} under multiplication: the only [[group (mathematics)|group]] of order two. 
The semigroups LO<sub>2</sub> and RO<sub>2</sub> are [[antiisomorphic]]. O<sub>2</sub>, {{nowrap|({0,1}, ∧)}} and {{nowrap|(Z<sub>2</sub>, +<sub>2</sub>)}} are [[commutativity|commutative]], LO<sub>2</sub> and RO<sub>2</sub> are noncommutative. LO<sub>2</sub>, RO<sub>2</sub> and {{nowrap|({0,1}, ∧)}} are [[band (algebra)|band]]s and also [[inverse semigroup]]s.



